Kallisto and Sleuth  
Group 34: Eric Bolander, Nathan Jih, Leah Kim	  
In the field of bioinformatics, RNA sequencing has emerged as a transformative technique for understanding gene expression. RNA sequencing is a particularly useful practice that can provide information about the diversity and activity we observe in cells. It is also an area where a large amount of varied data is generated which needs to be processed to draw conclusions about a biological sample. In a particular cell, there are several types of RNA that are present, each with its own function. For instance, mRNA is a crucial component to gene expression whereas snRNA and miRNA are also present in cells to assist with mRNA splicing and gene expression control. Furthermore, there are numerous molecules of RNA in a cell, generating a vast amount of data to be analyzed.  
	One of the primary goals of RNA sequencing data analysis is gene expression analysis, which involves identifying how genes are expressed under various conditions.. To understand this process, the RNA sequencing data needs to undergo processing and analysis. One of the first steps is to quantify the various RNA transcripts obtained from a sample, and there are several tools available to accomplish this and  help quantify and analyze the transcript data. One example of one of these pipelines would be using STAR, featureCounts, and DESeq2 which will quantify the RNA transcripts from the sequencing data and perform differential expression analysis based on the results. More recently, the Pachter lab has developed the tools Kallisto and Sleuth which can provide the same functionality as the previous pipeline but at a faster speed and using less memory.   
Kallisto is a tool that quantifies the abundances of RNA transcripts from high-throughput sequencing data. While STAR and other tools perform alignment to help identify and quantify RNA transcripts, Kallisto instead uses a more recently developed method of pseudoalignment.1 Typically, alignment refers to the process in which reads are mapped to a reference genome. Pseudoalignment instead utilizes de Bruijn graphs created from a known transcriptome to achieve transcript identification in a faster and more memory efficient manner.1 This algorithm is designed to minimise the computational time and burden while still providing accurate transcript quantification. After using Kallisto, the generated quantities of transcripts can be used as input for Sleuth, a companion tool to Kallisto, to perform differential expression analysis. 

![][image1]  
Figure 1: Example of a de Bruijn graph for pseudoalignment. Taken from *Near-optimal probabilistic RNA-seq quantification* by Bray, *et al.*, 2016\. 1

Sleuth employs variance decomposition as a key step in its analysis pipeline to improve the accuracy of identifying differences in gene or transcript expression.2 Variance decomposition refers to a statistical method in which the total variance is split into subsets that are both weighted separately based on the source of the variance. In the case of RNA-seq analysis, there is biological variance which reflects true differences in gene/transcript expression and inferential variance which represents the variance that can occur during quantification (e.g. errors in mapping reads to transcripts).  What separates Sleuth from other models, such as DESeq2 or Cuffdiff, is its ability to account for inferential variance. For example, if there are two conditions (e.g. treated vs. control), inferential variance might dominate if the gene has low expression or ambiguous read mappings and traditional methods might flag this gene as differentially expressed. Sleuth, through variance decomposition, recognizes high inferential variance and assigns less statistical weight to these observed differences.  By utilizing Kallisto’s quantification and variance estimates, Sleuth can separate biological variance from inferential variance before performing differential analysis.   
Sleuth demonstrates superior sensitivity for false discovery rate (FDR) thresholds compared to other tools like DESeq2, edgeR, or Cuffdiff2.2 Through testing on both simulated and biological data, Sleuth was shown to not only control FDR, but also effectively identify isoform-specific differential expression.2 Sleuth has flexibility to handle different types of RNA-seq analysis, such as gene-level and isoform-level. In gene-level analysis, RNA-seq data is used to study the aggregate expression of all transcripts connected to a gene. Whereas, in isoform-level analysis, RNA-seq data is used to study individual transcript variants produced by a gene. Isoform-level analysis allows researchers to focus on alternative-splicing events. While Sleuth excels in precision and speed, it is reliant on the quality of Kallisto quantifications. Together with Kallisto, Sleuth offers an easy to use workflow for transcript and gene-level analysis of RNA-seq data.   
   
	Compared to the STAR, featureCounts, and DESeq2 pipeline, Kallisto and Sleuth are faster and more memory efficient in general. While this may appear to be a strict improvement, these newer tools have their own limitations. The pseudoalignment algorithm that is at the core of Kallisto is limited by its inability to to properly handle sequencing errors, making this pipeline more reliant upon the quality of the sequencing data and unable to support as broad of a scope of applications for research as the other tools mentioned.3 This reliance upon sequencing quality would cause the tool to potentially call mismatches in the place of sequencing errors. Additionally, since Kallisto runs on pseudoalignment, the full alignments to a reference genome are not produced which can limit the applicability of the results for other research and analysis apart from those that only need the quantities and identities of the transcripts. Lastly, since the de Bruijn graphs used by Kallisto are based upon known transcriptome data, it is limited in its efficacy for completely novel samples. Taking these limitations into account, Kallisto and Sleuth are optimal tools for experiments aiming to perform transcript level analysis with a large amount of high quality RNA sequencing data, especially for situations where time or resources are limited.
